<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-20T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-20T13:00:00-05:00" n="697" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d697">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.6363/38: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-20T21:00:00+03:00">August 20,
                                    1942—9 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received August 20—4:27 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1466. The substance of Department’s 772, July 20, 10 p.m. was brought to
                            attention of General Spalding upon his arrival in Cairo and prior to his
                            departure for Iran and Iraq. He has now returned to Cairo en route to
                            Washington and informs me that owing to his other duties it was
                            impossible for him to investigate denial operations and plans affecting
                            Casoc oil fields.</p>
                        <pb facs="0595" n="583" xml:id="pg_583"/>
                        <p>I have shown him telegram No. 47 from AmLegation Jedda and he states that
                            he sees no reason why Casoc should not facilitate preparation of plan
                            for denial operation without regard to matter of possible active
                            preparation for such operations.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>